Let u\colon Y_\bullet \to X_\bullet be a morphism of topological simplicial spaces, with cone C(u). Let F be an abelian sheaf on X_\bullet and G an abelian sheaf on Y_\bullet , and let f\colon G\to F be a u-morphism. The cone C(f) of f is an abelian sheaf on C(u), and we set
2442hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1.xmlEquation6.3.2.1 \operatorname {H}^n(C(u),C(f)) = \operatorname {H}^n(X_\bullet \operatorname {mod} Y_\bullet , F\operatorname {mod} G). \tag{6.3.2.1}
These are the relative cohomology groups. We can easily show that they fit into a long exact sequence
2443hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.2hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.2.xmlEquation6.3.2.2 \ldots \to \operatorname {H}^i(X_\bullet \operatorname {mod} Y_\bullet , F\operatorname {mod} G) \to \operatorname {H}^i(X_\bullet ,F) \to \operatorname {H}^i(Y_\bullet ,G) \to \ldots . \tag{6.3.2.2}

A sheaf F on an r-simplicial topological space X_\bullet  induces a sheaf \delta  F on the diagonal simplicial space \delta  X_\bullet .
    It follows from the Cartier–Eilenberg–Zilber theorem that

    2129hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.2hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.2.xmlEquation6.4.2.2         \mathrm {R}\Gamma (X_\bullet ,K)         \xrightarrow {\sim } \mathrm {R}\Gamma (\delta  X_\bullet ,\delta  K).       \tag{6.4.2.2}

Let T be a left exact functor from \mathscr {A} to an abelian category \mathscr {B}.
    Suppose that every object of \mathscr {A} injects into an injective object.
    The functor T can then be "derived" to give the functors

    1057hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.1.xmlEquation7.1.3.1         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+(\mathscr {B})       \tag{7.1.3.1}       

    1058hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.2hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.2.xmlEquation7.1.3.2         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(\mathscr {B})       \tag{7.1.3.2}       

    1059hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.3hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.3.xmlEquation7.1.3.3         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(\mathscr {B}).       \tag{7.1.3.3}       

    They can be calculated as follows: if K' is a T-acyclic resolution (resp. a filtered resolution, resp. a bifiltered resolution) of K ( and ), then \mathrm {R} T(K)=T(K').

If K is filtered (resp. bifiltered), then \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*K is filtered (resp. bifiltered): we have

    2494hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.1.xmlEquation7.1.5.1         \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*         \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(X_\bullet )         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S_\bullet )       \tag{7.1.5.1}       

    2495hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.2hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.2.xmlEquation7.1.5.2         \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*         \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(X_\bullet )         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S_\bullet ).       \tag{7.1.5.2}

Let K be a complex of cosimplicial sheaves on S, endowed with an increasing filtration W.
    We define the diagonal filtration \delta (W,L) of W and L to be the increasing filtration of \mathrm {s} K given by

    2497hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.1.xmlEquation7.1.6.1         \begin {aligned}           \delta (W,L)_n(\mathrm {s} K)           &= \bigoplus _{p,q} W_{n+p}(K^{p,q})         \\&= \sum _p \mathrm {s}(W_{n+p}(K)) \cap  L^p(\mathrm {s} K).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.6.1}

The functor (K,W)\mapsto (\mathrm {s} K,\delta (W,L)) sends filtered quasi-isomorphisms to filtered quasi-isomorphisms, and defines

    2499hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.3hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.3.xmlEquation7.1.6.3         \begin {aligned}           (s,\delta )           \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S)         \\(K,W)           &\mapsto  (\mathrm {s} K,\delta (W,L))         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.6.3}       

    whence, by composition with ,

    2500hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.4hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.4.xmlEquation7.1.6.4         \begin {aligned}           (\mathrm {R}\Gamma ,\delta (-,L))           \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(X_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S)         \\(K,W)           &\mapsto  (\mathrm {R}\Gamma  K,\delta (W,L)).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.6.4}       

    From , we see that

    2501hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.5hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.5.xmlEquation7.1.6.5         \operatorname {Gr}_n^{\delta (W,L)}         = \bigoplus _p \mathrm {R}{a_p}_*(\operatorname {Gr}_{n+p}^W K)[-p].       \tag{7.1.6.5}

For example, for increasing W, the functor (K,W,F)\mapsto (K,\delta (W,L),F) sends bifiltered quasi-isomorphisms to bifiltered quasi-isomorphisms, and thus defines

    2503hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.1.xmlEquation7.1.7.1         \begin {aligned}           \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S)         \\(K,W,F)           &\mapsto  (K,\delta (W,L),F).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.7.1}       

    By composition with , we thus obtain

    2504hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.2hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.2.xmlEquation7.1.7.2         \begin {aligned}           \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(X_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S)         \\(K,W,F)           &\mapsto  (\mathrm {R}\Gamma  K,\delta (W,L),F).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.7.2}       

    and we have that

    2505hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.3hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.3.xmlEquation7.1.7.3         \operatorname {Gr}_n^{\delta (W,L)}(\mathrm {R}\Gamma  K,F)         = \bigoplus _p \mathrm {R}{a_p}_*(\operatorname {Gr}_{n+p}^W K,F)[-p]       \tag{7.1.7.3}       

    in \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S).

The claim (*)_0 is always true. Assume (*)_r, and let us prove (*)_{r+1}. We can suppose that 0\leqslant r\leqslant r_0. We have a diagram
\usepackage {amsmath} \usepackage {amssymb} \usepackage {tikz-cd} \begin {tikzcd} E_r(K,W) \ar [r,"d_r"] & E_r(K,W) \ar [r,"d_r"] & E_r(K,W) \\E_r(F^pK,W) \ar [r] \ar [u,hook] & E_r(F^pK,W) \ar [r] \ar [u,hook] & E_r(F^pK,W) \ar [u,hook,swap,"i"] \end {tikzcd}
and the image of the vertical inclusions is F_\mathrm {rec}^p(E_r(K,W)). Since i is injective,
\begin {aligned} F_\mathrm {rec}^p(E_{r+1}(K,W)) &= \operatorname {Im}\Big ( \operatorname {Ker} \big (F_\mathrm {rec}^pE_r(K,W)\xrightarrow {d_r}E_r(K,W) \big ) \to E_{r+1}(K,W) \Big ) \\&= \operatorname {Im}\Big ( \operatorname {Ker}\big ( E_r(F^pK,W)\xrightarrow {d_r}E_r(F^pK,W) \big ) \to E_{r+1}(K,W) \Big ) \\&= \operatorname {Im}\big ( E_{r+1}(F^pK,W) \to E_{r+1}(K,W) \big ). \end {aligned}
If r<r_0, then d_r is strictly compatible with F_\mathrm {rec}, whence d_rE_r(K,W)\cap E_r(F^pK,W) = d_rE_r(F^pK,W) and E_{r+1}(F^pK,W) thus injects into E_{r+1}(K,W). This proves (*)_{r+1}.

If is satisfied for r_0, and r\leqslant r_0+1, then we denote by F the filtration F_d=F_{d^*}=F_\mathrm {rec} of E_r(W,K). The exact sequences from (ii) of
\usepackage {amsmath} \usepackage {amssymb} \usepackage {tikz-cd} \begin {tikzcd} 0 & E_r(K/F^pK,W) \ar [l] && E_r(K/F^{p+1}K,W) \ar [ll] && 0 \\&& E_r(K,W) \ar [ul] \ar [ur] && E_r(\operatorname {Gr}_F^pK,W) \ar [ul] \ar [ur] \\0 \ar [r] & E_r(F^{p+1}K,W) \ar [rr] \ar [ur] && E_r(F^pK,W) \ar [ul] \ar [ur] && 0 \ar [ul] \end {tikzcd}
define, for r\leqslant r_0, an (autodual) isomorphism that is compatible with the differentials d_r, namely
960hodge-theory-iii-7.2.6.1hodge-theory-iii-7.2.6.1.xmlEquation7.2.6.1 \operatorname {Gr}_F^p(E_r(K,W)) \simeq E_r(\operatorname {Gr}_F^pK,W) \qquad \text {for }r\leqslant r_0. \tag{7.2.6.1}

Applying , taking L to be the complex
           0       \to  \operatorname {H}(F^pK)       \to  \operatorname {H}(K)       \to  \operatorname {H}(K/F^pK)       \to  0,     
    we see that:






        This sequence is exact, i.e. the differentials of K are strictly compatible with the filtration F;






        the filtration of \operatorname {H}(F^pK) induced by the filtration W of F^pK coincides with the filtration induced by the filtration W of \operatorname {H}(K);






        an analogous statement holds for K/F^pK.

Let A be as in . Then a Hodge A-complex K of weight n consists of
a complex K_A\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(A) such that \operatorname {H}^k(K_A) is an A-module of finite type for all k;
a filtration F on K_A\otimes \mathbb {C}, i.e. a filtered complex (K_\mathbb {C},F)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F(\mathbb {C}), and an isomorphism \alpha \colon K_\mathbb {C}\simeq K_A\otimes \mathbb {C} in \mathrm {D}^+(\mathbb {C}).

A mixed Hodge A-complex K consists of:






        a complex K_A\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(A) such that \operatorname {H}^k(K_A) is an A-module of finite type for all k;






        a filtered complex (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F(A\otimes \mathbb {Q}) (for an increasing filtration W) and an isomorphism K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}\simeq  K_A\otimes \mathbb {Q} in \mathrm {D}^+(A\otimes \mathbb {Q});






        a bifiltered complex (K_\mathbb {C},W,F)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F_w(\mathbb {C}) (for an increasing filtration W and a decreasing filtration F) and an isomorphism \alpha \colon (K_\mathbb {C},W)\simeq (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\otimes \mathbb {C} in \mathrm {D}^+F(\mathbb {C}).

A cohomological mixed Hodge A-complex K on a topological space X consists of:






        a complex K_A\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(X,A) such that \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^k(X,K_A) is an A-module of finite type for all k, and such that \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}(X,K_A)\otimes \mathbb {Q}\xrightarrow {\sim }\operatorname {\mathbb {H}}(X,K_A\otimes \mathbb {Q});






        a filtered complex (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F(X,A\otimes \mathbb {Q}) (for an increasing filtration W) and an isomorphism K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}\simeq  K_A\otimes \mathbb {Q} in \mathrm {D}^+(X,A\otimes \mathbb {Q});






        a bifiltered complex (K_\mathbb {C},W,F)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F_w(X,\mathbb {C}) (for an increasing filtration W and a decreasing filtration F) and an isomorphism \alpha \colon (K_\mathbb {C},W)\simeq (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\otimes \mathbb {C} in \mathrm {D}^+F(X,\mathbb {C}).

A DG mixed Hodge A-complex K consists of:






        a complex K_A\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(A\mathsf {-mod}_{\mathsf {DG}^+});





        a filtered complex (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F((A\otimes \mathbb {Q})\mathsf {-mod}_{\mathsf {DG}^+}), and is isomorphism K_A\otimes \mathbb {Q}\simeq  K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}} in \mathrm {D}^+;





        a bifiltered complex (K_\mathbb {C},F,W)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F_2(\mathbb {C}\mathsf {-mod}_{\mathsf {DG}^+}), and an isomorphism K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}\otimes \mathbb {C}\simeq  K_\mathbb {C} in \mathrm {D}^+F.

Let X_\bullet  be a simplicial topological space.
    A cohomological mixed Hodge A-complex K on X_\bullet  consists of:






        a complex K_A\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet ,A);






        a filtered complex (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F(X_\bullet ,A\otimes \mathbb {Q}), and an isomorphism K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}\simeq  K_A\otimes \mathbb {Q} in \mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet ,A\otimes \mathbb {Q});






        a bifiltered complex (K_\mathbb {C},W,F)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F_2(X_\bullet ,\mathbb {C}), and an isomorphism (K_\mathbb {C},W)\simeq (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\otimes \mathbb {C} in \mathrm {D}^+F(X_\bullet ,\mathbb {C}).

Let K be a cohomological mixed Hodge A-complex on X_\bullet .
    Write A\mathsf {-mod}_\mathsf {cosimp} to mean the category of cosimplicial A-modules.
    If we apply the functor \mathrm {R}\Gamma ^\bullet  to K, then we obtain






        a cosimplicial complex \mathrm {R}\Gamma ^\bullet  K_A\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(A\mathsf {-mod}_\mathsf {cosimp});






        a cosimplicial filtered complex \mathrm {R}\Gamma ^\bullet (K_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}},W)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F(A\otimes \mathbb {Q}\mathsf {-mod}_\mathsf {cosimp});






        a cosimplicial bifiltered complex \mathrm {R}\Gamma ^\bullet (K_\mathbb {C},W,F)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+F_2(\mathbb {C}\mathsf {-mod}_\mathsf {cosimp});






        isomorphisms as in (b) and (c) of  between these objects.

Let K be a DG mixed Hodge A-complex.
With the notation of , , and , (\mathrm {s} K,\delta (W,L),F) is a mixed Hodge A-complex.
We have
1244hodge-theory-iii-8.1.15.1hodge-theory-iii-8.1.15.1.xmlEquation8.1.15.1 {}_{\delta (W,L)}E_1^{ab}(\mathrm {s} K\otimes \mathbb {Q}) = \sum _{\substack {\alpha =\gamma -\beta \\b=\alpha +\beta }} \operatorname {H}^\alpha (\operatorname {Gr}_\beta ^W K^{\bullet \gamma }) \tag{8.1.15.1}
